<br>
I know you weren't being nasty when you said this, but thought I'd clear something up<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> while Cao has the option for a ND, i don't.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I leveled past 52 way post velious, prior to the ND even being an option.  Now, I have my ND, and I'm glad to have it, but I didn't know it would be an option when I decided to forgo Naggy/Vox.<br>
<br>
As for the rest of it, well, I have to agree with Celdor that the bard epic is, without question, a phenomenal piece for a bard. I have never questioned that bards should have sole rights to the white scale, I don't even think int casters should get a shot seeing as there are many cloaks that match or rival the WDSC.<br>
<br>
Beyond that, the one thing that bothers me, and the main reason I do not attend pickup raids with any of my characters is that they are no longer pick up raids.<br>
<br>
Jex readily admits that she skews the randoms in favor of her friends that attend the raids.  That's her right, and I'm not going to question it, but that negates the pickup raid aspect.  You are assigning a higher importance to a raid attendant because you know them or because they have been with you longer, or what not.<br>
<br>
That's not pickup raid rules, those are guild rules.  I expect my guild members and myself to know who would benefit more from an item and make decisions accordingly.  Pickup raids are different tho, you are asking people to attend and support you, to donate for costs, and yet offering no reward unless you have some prior knowledge of them.  <br>
<br>
I ask again, if the 45-49's are not necessary, not needed and merely &quot;cannon fodder&quot;, why even let them attend?  I propose it's because you simply wouldn't have the numbers otherwise.  So you are asking for raid attendants so &quot;person a&quot; can get a benefit.  You may be getting no personal &quot;loot&quot; benefit yourself, but you are assisting your friends, and that's equal in my eyes.<br>
<br>
I've said it before, I don't care what the raid rules are, if you attend, you agree to them, but you're not being honest with yourself, in my opinion. You're setting yourself up as this altruistic character who solely exists for the benefit of the masses who can't otherwise attend dragon raids.....but you're getting something.<br>
<br>
And Theo, I respect you and I respect your opinions, but I have to disagree with you on the earning your stripes aspect.  These are not guild raids.  You earn your stripes in guild raids, you expect to put forth effort for your guild members, with no prospect of reward to yourself, the exception being that you know your guild members will be there to back you up at a later date, when you are needing it.<br>
<br>
These are pickup raids, therefore your sole responsibility is to show up, follow directions and do your part.  You have NO responsibility beyond that.  In my opinion, and obviously there are many who disagree with me, but all are equal on a pickup raid.  <br>
<br>
If that was not the case, it'd be so easy to zone into any area, say, hey, I been camping this &quot;x&quot; for 8 weeks now, and you only just showed up, so I get to roll and you don't.  How well would that go over?  It wouldn't.  <br>
<br>
 <p><IMG SRC="http://www.taloncomics.com/Cao.JPG"><BR>
One part love, one part wild, one part glamour, one part child, a whole lotta fire, a little bit of ice, a whole lotta something you can't sacrifice</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utheodwynriddermark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TheodwynRiddermark</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/17/01 5:15:17 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://vivix.sysdudez.com/images/Theodwyn-thumb.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Heya Cao!<br>
<br>
You already knew I respect your opinions.  If you didn't, I'm happy to tell you I do.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I think I understand the point you're making.  So I feel I need to throw out a hypothetical question.<br>
<br>
I think you and several others will remember that once (and only once, lol) I called a dragon haste item on a raid.  I knew it was somewhat maverick of me, and I got a lot of grief for it.  I almost didn't make the numbers, and the muster took a lot longer.<br>
<br>
And in that case, I have to certainly agree with you.  It wasn't really a &quot;pick-up&quot; spirit raid per se.  And of course I learned that day (the hard way I might add), this view which I now espouse regarding the approval of the majority on a pick-up raid.  I very nearly didn't have it.<br>
<br>
I think I need to mention that by &quot;approval&quot; in this case I mean loot rules.  Obviously the burden of strategy and yelling instructions was still on me.  It's the risk we take when we lead raids.  By this I mean that the goal in a pick-up raid is signed off by the majority, although the strategic implementation rests with the leader.<br>
<br>
And if I follow you correctly, I must also agree that a pick-up &quot;clique&quot; that calls items for people doesn't necessarily confrom to the &quot;true spirit&quot; of a pick-up raid.<br>
<br>
So with all that preamble aside, I'd like to focus again on the policy of level cap on epic loot.<br>
<br>
I think that the level cap on epic loot isn't as discriminatory as to make it a &quot;guild-raid&quot; by nature.  For all one knows, that level 51 paladin who won a book may have never been to your raids before.  Therefore, does it not still conform to the spirit of &quot;pick-up&quot; in that case?<br>
<br>
The level cap on epic loot does not require that the person has been to every one of your raids since day one.  It implies that that person is part of the server community at large, not just your regular raidgroup.  And that they are trying for an epic drop which they need (need being a relative term, your mileage may vary).  Now, luck may not be with them, they may lose the roll, and thereafter attend all your raids (assuming you are always running the raid), but come to that point is the raidleader still responsible for their not getting a shot at the roll?  I don't think so, myself.  They rolled, they lost, they have to go again or give up.<br>
<br>
We've all seen a book called.  Usually with reluctance, and either by a person who has consistently attended and lost the roll.  Other times by a raid leader who is a friend of the unfortunate party.<br>
<br>
People call scales too, for the same reasons often enough.<br>
<br>
So in the purest sense of the term, I have to agree.  That's not really &quot;pure pick-up&quot; per se.<br>
<br>
But level capping the epic loot isn't the same matter, I don't think.  The level cap rule doesn't necessarily default the item to a specific person.  It gives the shot at those with the least time left to get it without slamming their head on the glass ceiling.<br>
<br>
I understand, we're discussing semantics here.  Nonetheless I find it interesting and would like to know other opinions.<br>
<br>
I think we're agreed that if you attend, you submit to the rules in place.  If you don't like them, don't go.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Oh, and the &quot;doing time&quot; term is something that I see people submit themselves to.  It's not a requirement, as we know.  Anyone can muster a raid, call their item, win it, and move on.  I must say though, I see quite a few people subscribe to the philosophy and practice it.  Far more than I see people mustering their own raids and surgically going for their items and washing their hands of the old world dragons.<br>
<br>
Cheers,<br>
Theo<br>
