<br>
Something you don't realize about the pickup raid environment is that, even with those simple responsibilities, people often don't live up to them. Some  examples:<br>
<br>
- Kerna, given the time he has been doing dragon pickups and respect level he has generated, generally can get enough people of the necessary classes to sign up pre event to make up planned lists, but a number of those people become no shows and he has to scramble for sufficient people of particular classes. <br>
<br>
-Of those who show up for a raid, the raiders will often have NO resist gear or extremely limited gear(despite what the leader has requested), and not let the raid leader know about it.<br>
<br>
-On a couple of pickup raids I've been on, there have been healers who refuse to heal rangers during a fight(being a ranger I did tend to notice). They don't tell the raid leader, they dont tell the group leader, and always say that &quot;rangers die too fast&quot;. <br>
<br>
-I also have seen classes that are supposed to be doing the healing for a group not doing so. I imagine that they were holding off so they have lots of mana for nuking, but since I would often end up dead before the nuke point, I couldn't tell for myself.<br>
<br>
- Despite the raid leader shouting for people to stay in one area, you always have those people, especially people who are there for the first time, wandering around to check things out. They aggro things from all over, running back to the group, generally over the medding casters.<br>
<br>
To be honest, I can't see why anyone would lead more than one pickup raid, but I am very happy that they do. I'm one of those people in the &quot;no/social/family&quot; guild void that would have NO chance to do something like take on a dragon. <br>
<br>
My thanks to all of the pickup raid leaders(especially Kerna and Jex since they are the ones that have put up with me the most. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ). I wish all of you could organize your raids on the public forum, but do understand why several of you went to private mailing lists.<br>
