</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uxurg002.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Xurg002</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/17/01 11:06:47 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I have a bitch about loot rules</span><hr size=1> Few random points to make...<br>
<br>
Yes, the way I put it made it seem like I was trying to be exclusive to &quot;my friends&quot; but I'll tell you that is not true, even though it is.  Explanation being this... any one who shows up to my raid is generally in... unless their level is low or they show up to late and there just is no room.  I took 8 groups to Naggy... why?  Because the people showed up and I didnt want to have to turn anyone away... why?  Because everyone deserves a shot at the fun or the loot.  Most of my raids only have about a dozen &quot;regulars&quot; the rest being random players who decide to give it a shot.  All those people are as important to me as the ones that I know from past experiences... otherwise I would be defaulting the items or turning people away.  I LOVE meeting new people and getting to know them... I also love knowing that perhaps I'll see them again.<br>
<br>
Another thing I have been doing recently on my raids (some people like the idea, some people dont) is that I allow people who are too high to fight the dragon to come along and help out in exchange for their shot at the items suitable for their class.  EXAMPLE:  Xentar (60 cleric) has attended a number of my raids and has helped with buffline/res's... in exchange for doing so he gets to roll on all items that the clerics get to roll on.  I have offered higher level bards (53+) an opportunity to come along, help with clearing giants, and sing the mana song for the buffline in exchange for a chance at the scale.  Same goes for paladins who can buff, or whomever else we can benefit from (regardless of if they are my friends or not)<br>
<br>
I have also told people/friends or guilds that if they knew someone who needed an item (specifically an epic piece) from Vox I would be more than happy to lead for them and allow them to set the loot rules.  As long as they set the rules and everyone is clear that it is &quot;their raid their rules&quot; and Im just the one in charge of the routine.<br>
<br>
As far as the &quot;friend favoring&quot;... anyone in the game who hasnt wronged me in some way is &quot;my friend&quot; and I believe that giving my all to help others is rewarding enough to know that its worth it despite the hassles that may come out of it.<br>
<br>
If someone has only raided with me once and they show great attitude, great team work, and they work hard to support the raid then they will rank right up there with the others who have been there from the beginning.  The people with the good attitudes are the ones I root for as far as loot... regardless of how long I have known them or how well.<br>
<br>
I meet new people each time I lead a dragon raid... and when those people come back I know Im doing something right.<br>
<br>
And thats all that matters to me.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ujexielia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jexielia</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_magentaspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 577<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/17/01 11:09:13 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I have a bitch about loot rules</span><hr size=1> bah wrong account<br>
